When enabled, the plugin will utilize th: When enabled, the plugin will utilise the full CPU power during scans, which may lead to faster scan times but could impact server performance. Disabling this option will make the plugin use less CPU, potentially reducing performance impact on your server during scans.
Specifies the duration (in milliseconds): Specifies the duration (in milliseconds) for which the plugin can utilise the CPU before pausing. Try decreasing this value if you notice performance issues during scans, especially on shared hosting environments.

Specifies the duration (in milliseconds) for which the plugin pauses to allow other processes to utilise the CPU. Try increasing this value if you notice performance issues during scans, especially on shared hosting environments.
Specifies the number of lines to process: Specifies the number of lines to process in each batch when reading files. Adjusting this value can help optimise performance and memory usage.
Specifies the size (in kilobytes) of the: Specifies the size (in kilobytes) of the content chunk read from a file in each iteration. Reducing this value may help prevent memory issues when processing large files.
Specifies the maximum execution time for: Specifies the maximum execution time for scan operations in seconds. Adjusting this value can help prevent long-running scans from causing timeout issues. Default is 0, which means the plugin will decide the best value.

Configure performance-related settings f: Configure performance-related settings for database cleanup operations and optimisation.
This method uses direct SQL queries for: This method uses direct SQL queries for cleanup operations. This can be faster but may bypass some WordPress mechanisms. For example, when deleting binned posts, this method will directly remove the posts from the database without triggering associated hooks and actions, which may leave related metadata, taxonomies, and other linked data intact and potentially lead to extra orphaned items.
This method uses WordPress native functi: This method uses WordPress native functions for cleanup operations. This ensures compatibility with WordPress but may be slower. For example, when deleting binned posts, this method will trigger all associated hooks and actions to delete related metadata, taxonomies, and other linked data, ensuring a thorough cleanup.

Choose the method used for database clea: Choose the method used for database cleanup operations. SQL offers direct database manipulation, while Native uses WordPress functions.
Specifies the number of rows to process: Specifies the number of rows to process in each batch when reading database tables. Reducing this value can help optimise performance and memory usage when dealing with large tables.
